er scripts\n\n**Project-Specific Context:**\n- espeak-ng uses `--with-libfuzzer=yes` configure flag\n- Build uses AFL++ compiler wrapper (`afl-clang-fast++`)\n- Address sanitizer is enabled (`-fsanitize=address`)\n- Architecture is x86_64\n\n**Build Progress Assessment:**\n- ✅ Docker image built successfully\n- ✅ Configuration completed (`./configure --with-libfuzzer=yes`)\n- ✅ All source files compiled successfully  \n- ❌ Linking failed due to missing fuzzer library\n\n**Priority Investigation Areas:**\n1. Check `/src/aflplusplus/` directory for fuzzer libraries\n2. Examine the actual linker command in Makefile:1394\n3. Verify if `-fsanitize=fuzzer` flag is being used correctly\n4. Check for alternative fuzzer library names (e.g., `libclang_rt.fuzzer-x86_64.a`)\n\n--- 【LESSONS FROM PREVIOUS ATTEMPTS】 ---\n- [Attempt 2] Successfully fixed boringssl compilation error by adding character-conversion warning suppression flags. However, build now fails at nghttp2 configuration stage due to c-ares version mismatch (requires >=1.16.0, system has 1.15.0). The nghttp2 configure script enables --enable-app on Linux, which depends on c-ares. This reveals a layered dependency issue: fixing compiler warnings exposed underlying dependency version problem. Need to either update c-ares, disable --enable-app, or find alternative dependency resolution.\n- [Attempt 3] Successfully fixed c-ares dependency issue by disabling --enable-app for nghttp2. Build progressed through configuration stage (nghttp2 configured with Applications: no, HTTP/3: yes). However, compilation now fails due to missing C++20 <span> header. The AFL++ Clang compiler is using -std=gnu++20 but standard library appears incomplete. This reveals a C++20 standard library compatibility issue in the AFL++ Clang environment. Need to either: 1) Ensure complete C++20 stdlib, 2) Use C++17 instead of C++20, or 3) Patch nghttp2 to avoid <span> dependency.\n- [Attempt 1] Build progressed to linking stage but missing fuzzer run